{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"165ba637-1e61-4712-a63b-abe8f89d594f","content":"Use **`dotnet-trace`** — it's the lightest option that works well inside containers.\n\n**Steps:**\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool inside the pod\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (speedscope format is portable)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --format speedscope\n```\n\nPress `Enter` or `Ctrl+C` to stop collection. Copy the file out:\n\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.speedscope.json ./trace.speedscope.json\n```\n\nOpen it at [https://www.speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app) or in Visual Studio / PerfView (use `--format nettrace` for those).\n\n**Tips:**\n- Collect for **30–60 seconds** under load to get a representative sample.\n- If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the image), grab the standalone binary from the [dotnet-diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics).\n- For **production-safe** collection with no SDK at all, use a **sidecar** with `dotnet-monitor`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e3840ad4-f31d-4ce0-9b7c-d78163978272","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question - no code changes needed, just advice.","outputTokens":367,"requestId":"AC0E:37A40F:13D2E36:164308C:6A06715E"},"id":"c2c09877-a067-4d62-9d24-fef5cd852d5a","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:05:45.303Z","parentId":"e9619bd1-990c-448e-aa7e-817880d64ffd"}
